ick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde de Chaumont-en-Vexin was born in 1217, in Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Bernard de Chaumont-en-Vexin, was 37 and her mother, Aélis de Gisors, was 24. She had at least 1 daughter with Mathieu II de Beauvoir. She died in 1279, in Bailleul, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 62, and was buried in Bailleul, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France."},"et":{"1217–1279":"1217–1279","1211–1266":"1211–1266","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1242–1300":"1242–1300","1180–1238":"1180–1238","1193–1252":"1193–1252","1217":"1217","1238":"1238","1205":"1205","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1266":"1266","1211":"1211","1242":"1242","1264":"1264","1252":"1252","1193":"1193","1180":"1180","Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France":"Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Beauvoir, Manche, Normandie, France":"Beauvoir, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Bailleul, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France":"Bailleul, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Pran